  "market_context": "Prior day closed below previous day high (failure to close over), establishing bearish daily bias. London session began with a stop hunt into a fair value gap, followed by aggressive displacement downward during the London killzone (02:00–05:00 EST).",
  "key_observation": "Price failed to close above the previous day high, signaling bearish daily bias; London session then swept liquidity into a fair value gap before strong downward displacement.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Analyst observed on daily chart that price failed to close over the previous day high, establishing a bearish daily bias and expecting price to seek lower levels (previous day low or swing point).",
    "Step 2: Dropped to hourly chart, marked midnight open, and identified a stop hunt (liquidity sweep) into a fair value gap during London session.",
    "Step 3: Noted aggressive displacement off the fair value gap and confirmed the timing aligned with London killzone, prompting entry consideration at the FVG.",
    "Step 4: Defined trade setup: short entry at the fair value gap, stop above the sweep high, target at previous day low and a nearby swing point.",
    "Step 5: Watched price aggressively move down to previous day low, then continue further to the identified swing point, confirming the trade."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade executed as short at FVG during London session; price moved aggressively down to previous day low and continued to the swing point, achieving multi-R reward.",
  "lessons": "Daily bias derived from failure to close over prior day high is highly reliable; London killzone often provides high-probability FVG entries after liquidity sweeps, especially when aligned with HTF structure.",
